---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Guides | SexualHarassmentCalc';
const description = 'In-depth guides on workplace sexual harassment claims: how settlements are calculated, claim types, post-incident steps, and common misconceptions.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Guides</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by our editorial team. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>
    Four practitioner-reviewed deep dives on the parts of a workplace sexual harassment claim that most affect outcome:
    how damages are calculated, which claim type fits which facts, what to do in the days and weeks after an incident,
    and the misconceptions that cost plaintiffs the most leverage.
  </p>

  <h2><a href="/guides/how-sexual-harassment-settlements-are-calculated">How sexual harassment settlements are calculated</a></h2>
  <p>
    The damages components recognized under Title VII, the 42 U.S.C. &sect; 1981a(b)(3) employer-size cap on combined
    compensatory and punitive damages, state-law overlays that uncap recovery (California FEHA, NY HRL, NJ LAD, IL HRA, MA c. 151B),
    fee-shifting under 42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-5(k), and the duty to mitigate. Worked examples included.
  </p>

  <h2><a href="/guides/types-of-workplace-harassment">Types of workplace harassment</a></h2>
  <p>
    Quid pro quo, hostile work environment (the &ldquo;severe or pervasive&rdquo; standard from <em>Harris v. Forklift</em>),
    retaliation under 42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-3, same-sex harassment after <em>Oncale</em>, the <em>Faragher</em>/<em>Ellerth</em>
    affirmative defense, and intersectional harassment claims that combine sex with another protected characteristic.
  </p>

  <h2><a href="/guides/what-to-do-after-workplace-harassment">What to do after workplace harassment</a></h2>
  <p>
    Document everything, preserve evidence, file an internal HR complaint in writing, file an EEOC or state-agency charge before
    the deadline runs, consult an employment plaintiff&rsquo;s attorney, understand retaliation protections, and avoid the severance
    trap. Practical sequencing, not a legal opinion.
  </p>

  <h2><a href="/guides/common-sexual-harassment-claim-misconceptions">Common sexual harassment claim misconceptions</a></h2>
  <p>
    Fifteen widespread myths corrected against the actual statute and case law: that harassment must be physical, that you must
    report immediately, that you must use HR first, that prior conduct of the plaintiff is admissible (Federal Rule of Evidence 412
    says otherwise), and more.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
